                           "explanation":"A mutual fund’s share price is different than its NAV.  As is the case with individual stocks, a fund’s <b>share price</b> is the price you would pay for one share of that fund.  The <b>NAV</b> is the total value of all securities in the portfolio, less any liabilities, divided by the total number of fund shares outstanding.  It is analogous to an individual stock’s <b>book value</b>.  Just as stocks do not always trade at or above their book values, neither do funds."
