                     "answers":[
                        {
                           "answer":"A)  Betting against the overall direction of the market",
                           "explanation":"Almost.  As history has shown, stocks tend to appreciate over time, which means that in short selling you’re betting against the overall direction of the market.  This is true, but it’s not the only right answer here…"
                        },
                        {
                           "answer":"B)  Losses can be infinite",
                           "explanation":"Almost.  Short sale losses have unlimited downside.  A short sale loses when the stock price rises and a stock is (theoretically, at least) not limited in how high it can go.  This is true, but it’s not the only right answer here…"
                        },
                        {
                           "answer":"C)  Involves using borrowed money",
                           "explanation":"Almost.  Short selling requires you to open a margin account, in which you borrow money from your brokerage firm and use your investment as collateral.  If the stock price (and hence your liability) increases above a certain level, you’ll be subject to margin calls, forcing you to either put in more money for collateral or liquidate your position.  This is true, but it’s not the only right answer here…"
                        },
                        {
                           "answer":"D)  Timing is everything",
